Family doctor (@lifeofdrmom) and dermatologist (@russwong.md team up to share their sleep positions.

@lifeofdrmom likes to sleep on her side which may reduce back pain, heartburn and snoring.

@russwong.md likes to sleep on his back as sleeping on your back may reduce wrinkles. By sleeping on your back you avoid mechanical compression of your face during sleep. Studies suggest that compression of your skin can reinforce expression lines and cause wrinkles over time (Anson et al 2016).

